  "text": "## End-to-End Flow: Creating a Kubernetes Deployment\n\nWhen a client application creates a Kubernetes Deployment, the request flows through three distinct layers:\n\n### 1. Client Library Layer (kubernetes-client-go)\n\nThe flow begins in the **client library** (`sg-evals/kubernetes-client-go`). An application calls `deploymentsClient.Create(context.TODO(), deployment, metav1.CreateOptions{})` (as seen in the example at `examples/create-update-delete-deployment/main.go:103`).\n\nThis call is dispatched to the generated `Client.Create` method in `gentype/type.go:244`. This method constructs an HTTP POST request using the REST client:\n```go\nerr := c.client.Post().\n    UseProtobufAsDefaultIfPreferred(c.prefersProtobuf).\n    NamespaceIfScoped(c.namespace, c.namespace != \"\").\n    Resource(c.resource).\n    VersionedParams(&opts, c.parameterCodec).\n    Body(obj).\n    Do(ctx).\n    Into(result)\n```\n\nThe POST request is sent to the Kubernetes API server at the endpoint `/api/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/deployments` with the Deployment object serialized in the request body.\n\n### 2. API Server Layer (kubernetes/kubernetes)\n\nThe Kubernetes API server receives the HTTP POST request and routes it to the **REST storage handler** for Deployments (`pkg/registry/apps/deployment/storage/storage.go`). The storage is configured with a `genericregistry.Store` that implements the `rest.Storage` interface.\n\nWhen the request arrives, the `Store.Create` method in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/registry/generic/registry/store.go:446` is invoked. This method performs critical validation and preparation:\n\n1. **Strategy validation** (`rest.BeforeCreate`, line 501): Applies the Deployment creation strategy hooks that validate resource quotas, set defaults, and prepare the object.\n2. **Admission control** (line 506-509): Runs configured admission plugins to validate the request.\n3. **Object preparation** (lines 481-488): Fills in system-managed fields (creation timestamp, resource version, etc.) and generates names if needed.\n4. **Storage call** (line 526): After all validations pass, it calls `e.Storage.Create(ctx, key, obj, out, ttl, dryrun.IsDryRun(options.DryRun))` to persist the object.\n\n### 3. Storage Layer (etcd-io-etcd)\n\nThe storage backend is implemented in **etcd3** (`staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/etcd3/store.go`). The `store.Create` method (line 241) executes the following steps:\n\n1. **Encoding** (line 260): Serializes the Deployment object using the registered codec: `data, err := runtime.Encode(s.codec, obj)`\n2. **Transformation** (line 275): Applies data transformation for encryption if enabled: `newData, err := s.transformer.TransformToStorage(ctx, data, ...)`\n3. **Optimistic Put** (line 283): Calls the etcd Kubernetes client's optimistic put operation: `s.client.Kubernetes.OptimisticPut(ctx, preparedKey, newData, 0, kubernetes.PutOptions{LeaseID: lease})`\n\nThe `OptimisticPut` method in `client/v3/kubernetes/client.go:83` constructs an etcd **transaction** with an optimistic concurrency check:\n\n```go\ntxn := k.KV.Txn(ctx).If(\n    clientv3.Compare(clientv3.ModRevision(key), \"=\", expectedRevision),\n).Then(\n    clientv3.OpPut(key, string(value), clientv3.WithLease(opts.LeaseID)),\n)\ntxnResp, err := txn.Commit()\n```\n\nThis transaction:\n- Checks that the key doesn't exist (ModRevision = 0)\n- If the check passes, executes a Put operation to store the Deployment data\n- Attaches the lease if a TTL was specified (for automatic cleanup on expiration)\n- Commits the transaction to etcd\n\nOnce the transaction is committed, the **etcd server** applies the request. The `applierV3backend.Put` method in `server/etcdserver/apply.go:249` processes the Put request:\n\n1. It creates an MVCC write transaction if needed\n2. It retrieves the previous key-value pair if needed (for PrevKv semantics)\n3. Most critically, it calls `txn.Put(p.Key, val, leaseID)` (line 300) which:\n   - Writes the key-value pair to the in-memory MVCC store\n   - Updates the modification revision\n   - Increments the global revision counter\n   - Persists the data to the underlying etcd backend\n\nThe data is now stored in etcd's persistent key-value store, and the response is propagated back through the layers, with each layer adding metadata (revision numbers, creation timestamps, etc.) until the client receives the created Deployment object.\n\n## Summary of Key Functions\n\n| Layer | Repository | File | Function | Purpose |\n|-------|-----------|------|----------|----------|\n| **Client** | sg-evals/kubernetes-client-go | gentype/type.go:244 | `Client.Create` | Sends HTTP POST with Deployment data |\n| **API Server** | sg-evals/kubernetes-kubernetes | staging/.../registry/store.go:446 | `Store.Create` | Validates and routes to storage |\n| **Storage** | sg-evals/kubernetes-kubernetes | staging/.../etcd3/store.go:241 | `store.Create` | Encodes and calls etcd Put |\n| **etcd Client** | sg-evals/etcd-io-etcd | client/v3/kubernetes/client.go:83 | `Client.OptimisticPut` | Creates transaction with Put operation |\n| **etcd Server** | sg-evals/etcd-io-etcd | server/etcdserver/apply.go:249 | `applierV3backend.Put` | Applies Put to MVCC store and persists |\n\nThis architecture ensures that Deployment creation is atomic (via transactions), validated at multiple levels (client-side, server-side, admission), and durably persisted to the distributed etcd store."
